    comment: '<p>The HTML <code>&#x3C;thead></code>, <code>&#x3C;tbody></code> and <code>&#x3C;tfoot></code> elements are used in conjunction with the <code>&#x3C;table></code> element to section the table into 3 parts.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>&#x3C;thead></code>: is used to group <code>&#x3C;tr></code> elements as the header of an HTML table.</li>\n<li><code>&#x3C;tbody></code>: is used to group <code>&#x3C;tr></code> elements as the body of an HTML table.</li>\n<li><code>&#x3C;tfoot></code>: is used to group <code>&#x3C;tr></code> elements as the footer of an HTML table.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>There are 2 key benefits(both mentioned above) of using these elements:\n1. The table body can scroll independently of the header and footer.\n2. Tables will print with header/footer on top/bottom when spanning multiple pages</p>\n<p><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="320" height="139"><g fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"><rect width="320" height="139" fill="#FFF" rx="9"/><path stroke="#000" stroke-linecap="square" stroke-width="2" d="M16.5 29.5h288.01563"/><path fill="#E3E3E3" d="M15 45h288v14H15zm0 30h288v14H15zm0 30h288v14H15z"/><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Medium, Roboto" font-size="10" font-weight="400"><tspan x="21" y="23">Character</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="21" y="41">Colegogia</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="21" y="55">Driscollcheek</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="21" y="69">Helltinez</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="21" y="84">Fostershu</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="21" y="98">Grrramirez</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="21" y="113">Thocrusha</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="117" y="113">Giant</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="214" y="113">Warrior</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="117" y="98">Troll</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="214" y="98">Blacksmith</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="117" y="84">Dragonia</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="214" y="84">Warrior</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="117" y="69">Human</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="214" y="69">Warrior</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="117" y="55">Gnome</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="214" y="55">Bard</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="117" y="41">Giant</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="214" y="41">Warrior</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Medium, Roboto" font-size="10" font-weight="400"><tspan x="117" y="23">Race</tspan></text><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Medium, Roboto" font-size="10" font-weight="400"><tspan x="214" y="23">Class</tspan></text><path stroke="#979797" stroke-linecap="square" d="M15.5 108.5h288"/><path fill="#FFF" d="M15 109h288v14H15z"/><text fill="#262626" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="10"><tspan x="21" y="122">Fantasy Game Characters</tspan></text></g></svg></p>\n<!--[View CodePen](https://codepen.io/enkidevs/pen/JBXyoJ)-->\n<p>Using these elements provides useful semantic information for screen readers, printers and other accessibility purposes.</p>\n<p>The <code>&#x3C;thead></code>, <code>&#x3C;tbody></code>, and <code>&#x3C;tfoot></code> elements have no default visual effects.</p>\n<p>Furthermore, there are some important usage notes for these elements. These are:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>If your table has a <code>&#x3C;thead></code> element, the <code>&#x3C;tbody></code> element has to come after it.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>If your table has a <code>&#x3C;tbody></code> element, all <code>&#x3C;tr></code> elements within that table have to be a child of the <code>&#x3C;tbody></code> and cannot reside outside the <code>&#x3C;tbody></code> element.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>When a table is printed, the header and footer, or the <code>&#x3C;thead></code> and <code>&#x3C;tfoot></code> elements content is printed on every page, while the <code>&#x3C;tbody></code> element\'s content differs from page to page.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>If the table is too large for the window/screen it is presented on, the user agent can allow the user to scroll each table element separately, that is the <code>&#x3C;thead></code>, <code>&#x3C;tbody></code>, <code>&#x3C;tfoot></code> and the <code>&#x3C;caption></code> elements.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>If necessary, you can use more than one <code>&#x3C;tbody></code> element within a table. This is very useful for larger tables, where you want to divide the table into separate sections and give each section a different formatting. Also, when dividing the table with multiple <code>&#x3C;tbody></code> elements, each <code>&#x3C;tbody></code> element can have its own header row.</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Having a header row doesn\'t mean having multiple <code>&#x3C;thead></code> elements, this is not allowed. What this means is each top row of the <code>&#x3C;tbody></code> element can be made a header with the appropriate combination of <code>&#x3C;tr></code> and <code>&#x3C;th></code> elements.</p>\n<p>For a similar and larger example with CSS and multiple <code>&#x3C;tbody></code> elements, check the <code>codepen example</code> link under the more info section at the bottom of this insight.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n',
